      <hedline>
        <hl1>$5 MILLION, TIMES TWO</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By ELIZABETH OLSON</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Olson, Elizabeth</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>E Gerald Corrigan, former chief executive of Federal Reserve Bank of New York, gives $5 million to his college Fairfield University in Connecticut; he also gave same amount to Fordham University in March, where he earned his master's degree and doctorate in economics (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>When it comes to his alma maters, E. Gerald Corrigan, former chief executive of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, is a generous man. This month, he gave $5 million to his college, Fairfield University, the Jesuit institution in Connecticut where he got his undergraduate degree, majoring in economics, in 1963. Mr. Corrigan, 66, now a managing director at Goldman Sachs, serves on Fairfield's board of trustees.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>When it comes to his alma maters, E. Gerald Corrigan, former chief executive of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, is a generous man. This month, he gave $5 million to his college, Fairfield University, the Jesuit institution in Connecticut where he got his undergraduate degree, majoring in economics, in 1963. Mr. Corrigan, 66, now a managing director at Goldman Sachs, serves on Fairfield's board of trustees.</p>
        <p>In March, he also gave the same amount to Fordham, another Jesuit university, where he earned his master's degree and doctorate in economics.</p>
        <p>ELIZABETH OLSON</p>
        <p>OPENERS: SUITS</p>
      </block>
